						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">In a demo, intro, or other program with limited interactivity, you have a lot more leeway than you have with a game. In a game, you have a lot of objects' state to keep in the NES's 2 KB of built-in work RAM, you have to make time for the OAM update, and you have to run AI and physics during the 'draw' time. In a demo, you don't.</div>
<br />
<br />I'll exclusively update the PPU during vblank. All the physics and object handling is done during rendering, not drawing. I'll use buffers to store everything I have to draw, so that drawing is just a matter of copying bytes. I agree with the RAM usage thing though, but that's the only difference. Besides, in the other mentioned thread, about Battletoads (a full featured game), it did update a lot of stuff and did OAM updates also.
<br />
<br />Well, I'll just be safe and write few rows/columns per frame. The question about pattern table updates was for another project anyway, not for the platformer.</div>

